Detailed Description

A Stored Bookmark Managed Object.

May be a Collection, Folder, Bookmark or Separator

Member Function Documentation

- (void) addTags: (id)  additionalTags  

Adds additional tags to the receivers tags set.

Note that we store 'tags' as a simple attribute, a set of NSStrings, and not a relationship. So we don't have the 'addTags:' accessor that would be provided by Core Data if 'tags' was a relationship.

Parameters:
additionalTags Either an NSArray* or NSSet* of strings, the new tags to be added

- (void) appendChildren: (NSArray*)  children  

Appends an ordered array of new children to the children of the receiver.

The index of the first element in the array is set to be one more than the highest existing index in the receiver's set of children, and then they increase from there.

Parameters:
children The children to be appended.

- (void) appendRssArticles: (NSArray*)  articles  

Appends an ordered array of new RSS articles to the rssArticles of the receiver.

The index of the first element in the array is set to be one more than the highest existing index in the receiver's set of rssArticles, and then they increase from there.

Parameters:
articles The articles to be appended.

- (void) assembleAsTreeWithBar: (Stark*)  bar
menu: (Stark*)  menu
unfiled: (Stark*)  unfiled
ohared: (Stark*)  ohared 

Assuming receiver is the root of a tree, given optionally the four immoveable branches, grafts them together properly and cleans everything up.

Finds immoveable branches either as arguments or already in receiver's children: If bar is nil, will examine receiver's children for item with starype = StarypeBar. If menu is nil, will examine receiver's children for item with starype = StarypeMenu. If unfiled is nil, will examine receiver's children for item with starype = StarypeUnfiled. If shared is nil, will examine receiver's children for item with starype = StarypeOhared.

After finding these four fixtures,

  1. Sets the name the four fixtures.
  2. Sets the starypes of the four fixtures and that of the receiver.
  3. Sets the positions of the four fixtures to 0,1,2,3 within the receiver's children
The receiver may already have other soft folders as children. The positions of these children will be adjusted as needed.

This method is invoked at the end of readExternalNoPrereqs by Extore subclasses. The reason for step 3 is that the ixternalizeFromStartainer:: methods need a known configuration for the source: Are the fixtures children of root, or are they not? I believe that, in some subclasses, the readExternalNoPrereqs method places them as children of root, but others do not. It might be nice to someday go through all of those subclasses, change if needed so that they do ^not^ place the fixtures into root, then eliminate step 3 above, and finally modify ixternalizeFromStartainer:: methods so as to access the fixtures using -bar, -menu, -unfiled, and -oshared instead of iterating through root's children.

Parameters:
bar The bar of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
menu The menu of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
unfiled The unfiled of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.
shared The shared of the tree to be assembled. May be nil.

- (id) bmxBk  

Gets the BmxBk at the root of the receiver's lineage.

This is actually calculated for all except the greatest ancestor which should have had its key set with setBmxBk:. It may return nil if self or one of its ancestors has been removed and is an orphan.

Returns:
The BmxBk at the root of the receiver's lineage, which may be nil.

- (void) createFoldersFromTags: (BkmmCreateFoldersFromTags)  createFoldersFromTags  

Folder-izes a Stark containing only one generation of children, by creating folders named after bookmarks' tags and moving the bookmarks into them.

Places each child in a new subfolder of the receiver, named after one of the receiver's tags. If doMultiple == YES, creates a subfolder for each tag and places a copy of the receiver in each of the new subfolders. Otherwise, arbitrarily picks only one and places the tagged child into it.

Parameters:
createFoldersFromTags Specifies whether no folders should be created, one folder may be created, or multiple folders, each containing a copy of the tagged child should be created for children that have multiple tags. If this value is BkmmCreateFoldersFromTagsNone, this method is a no-op.

- (Stark *) deepOrphanCopySameIDs: (BOOL)  sameIDs
startainer: (id <Startainer>)  startainer 

Returns a deep copy (descendants in parent/child relationships) of the receiver, with nodes inserted into a specified BmxBk's store.

This is indeed a 'copy' method in the memory-management sense.

Parameters:
sameIDs If YES, the Starks in the result tree will have the same externalIdentifier key values as the corresponding nodes in the receiver. If NO, the externalIdentifier key values will be removed.
Returns:
An tree of allocated copies of the receiver, not autoreleased.

- (Stark *) replicatedOrphanStarkWithNoIDInStartainer: (id<Startainer>)  startainer  

Invokes replicatedOrphanStarkWithSameID:startainer: with sameID = YES.

Provided as a convenience to simplify the signature of replicatedStarkInBmxBk:sameID: so that methods like performSelector: can be used to recursively invoke it without having to create a (gasp!) NSInvocation.

Parameters:
startainer The startainer into whose managed object context the new stark should be inserted.

- (Stark *) replicatedOrphanStarkWithSameID: (BOOL)  sameID
startainer: (id <Startainer>)  startainer 

Returns an new, inserted stark containing most of the receiver's current non-nil attributes as keys and values, and also containing a key KEY_CHILDREN with an empty NSMutableArray.

This method is for copying Starks. Therefore, the key KEY_PARENT is never copied. If sameID is NO, the KEY_EXTERNAL_IDENTIFIER key is also omitted from the result. This method is used as a first step in making a copy of a Stark. The new Stark returned will be inserted into the managed object context of the given startainer. The empty array is set so that children may subsequently be set in a recursive method. Also, a new externalIdentifier may later be set, and a new parent. In the name, the word "replica" is used instead of "copy", so as to not have a Cocoa memory management implication.

Parameters:
sameID If YES, and if the receiver has an object for key KEY_EXTERNAL_IDENTIFIER", that key/value pair appears in the result. If NO, the KEY_EXTERNAL_IDENTIFIER key/value pair is always omitted.
startainer The startainer into whose managed object context the new stark should be inserted.
Returns:
An autoreleased NSDictionary replicating the attributes of the receiver as described.

- (void) setIsSortable: (NSNumber*)  isSortable  

setter for the property isSortable

This method overrides Core Data's dynamically- generated method. The difference is that it only sets the value if the desired value is different than the default value for this stark. Otherwise, it removes the value for the key isSortable.

- (void) setToBkmmParent: (Stark*)  newParent
atIndex: (unsigned int)  newIndex 

Adds a parent/child relationship.

To add as last child, pass newIndex=NSNotFound If index given would leave a gap between receiver and siblings, adds as last sibling instead. To make orphan, pass newParent = nil ; Does not remove from previous parent. Use moveToBkmmParent: for that. This method is primitive in the sense that it does not set up undo, tellTreeModified, increment change count, update windows, show items, or order windows.

Parameters:
newParent The new parent to which the receiver should be added as a child, or nil if the desired action is to orphan the receiver.
newIndex The index (position) at which the receiver should be added
